◆ bcm_ptp_clock_create()

int bcm_ptp_clock_create ( int  unit,
bcm_ptp_stack_id_t  ptp_id,
bcm_ptp_clock_info_t *  clock_info 
)

Create PTP Clock instance.

Creates, or re-creates, a PTP clock with the values specified in clock_info. The created clock will have empty master and slave tables, and all clock ports will have a default configuration that should be overridden via a call to bcm_ptp_clock_port_configure . For those values in the clock_info structure that are not otherwise run-time configurable (e.g. num_ports or flags), the clock can be re-created with updated values. Re-creation will result in empty master and slave tables, and ports that require configuration. One limitation on re-creation is that num_ports may not be increased above the value specified on the first clock creation. In the case where it is desired to create a single-port OC that may be later re-created as a multi-port BC, it is thus necessary to first create the clock with the maximal number of ports, then to re-create it as a single port OC.

Parameters
[in]unitUnit number.
[in]ptp_idPTP Stack ID
[in,out]clock_info(IN/OUT) PTP Clock Information

◆ bcm_ptp_clock_current_dataset_get()

int bcm_ptp_clock_current_dataset_get ( int  unit,
bcm_ptp_stack_id_t  ptp_id,
int  clock_num,
bcm_ptp_current_dataset_t *  dataset 
)

Get PTP Clock instance current dataset.

Get PTP Clock instance current dataset. The 'offset_from_master' field is the time difference between master and slave as computed by the slave. It is scaled nanoseconds as defined in the IEEE 1588v2 spec. The scaledNanoseconds is the time interval expressed in units of nanoseconds and multiplied by 2^16. Although it is defined as an unsigned 64bit integer in the API, the offset can even be negative. Users can typecast the variable to a signed datatype and convert to unscaled value (example below) to get the actual offset from master in nanoseconds.

offset_nanoseconds = (long long)cur_data_set.offset_from_master/(long long)PTP_CURRENT_DATASET_OFFSET_FROM_MASTER_SCALEFACTOR;
offset_fraction = cur_data_set.offset_from_master - (decval * PTP_CURRENT_DATASET_OFFSET_FROM_MASTER_SCALEFACTOR);
offset_fraction = (offset_fraction >= 0) ? offset_fraction : -offset_fraction;
offset from master in unscaled nanoseconds = offset_nanoseconds.offset_fraction;
Parameters
[in]unitUnit number.
[in]ptp_idPTP Stack ID
[in]clock_numPTP Clock Number
[out]datasetCurrent Data Set

◆ bcm_ptp_clock_port_configure()

int bcm_ptp_clock_port_configure ( int  unit,
bcm_ptp_stack_id_t  ptp_id,
int  clock_num,
uint32  clock_port,
bcm_ptp_clock_port_info_t *  info 
)

Configure PTP Clock Port information.

Configures PTP Clock Port information. In addition to setting the port address (IPv4, IPv6, or MAC for L2) and local MAC, the raw L2 headers for outgoing multicast packets are specified, to permit arbitrary outgoing VLAN or other routing information. Incoming packets are checked for assignment to clock ports starting at port 1. The matching criteria for assigning a packet to a clock port are given in rx_packets_criteria_mask. The VLAN and ingress port are only checked if the corresponding criteria mask bits are set. Setting the BCM_PTP_RXMAP_MATCH_ANY_ADDR bit provides the ability to have a 'wildcard' port that will accept incoming PTP traffic regardless of the destination address. This should generally only be set on the last clock port, as otherwise this port will accept packets that would otherwise be accepted by a different clock port.

Parameters
[in]unitUnit number.
[in]ptp_idPTP Stack ID
[in]clock_numPTP Clock Number
[in]clock_portClock Port
[in]infoPTP Clock Info

◆ bcm_ptp_signaling_arbiter_register()

int bcm_ptp_signaling_arbiter_register ( int  unit,
bcm_ptp_stack_id_t  ptp_id,
int  clock_num,
bcm_ptp_signaling_arbiter_t  arb,
void *  user_data 
)

Register an arbiter for handling PTP signaling logic.

Register an arbiter callback for handling PTP signaling logic. This function will be called whenever a signaling message is received, with the parsed fields in the bcm_ptp_cb_signaling_arbiter_msg_t struct. The arbiter function can change these fields as desired (to update the grant duration, for example). The arbiter then can return bcmPTPCallbackReject, to drop the signaling message, or bcmPTPCallbackAccept, to accept it. Note that a signaling grant response with a grant duration of 0 is the PTP mechanism to inform the slave that the grant was not accepted.

Parameters
[in]unitUnit number.
[in]ptp_idPTP Stack ID
[in]clock_numPTP Clock Number
[in]arbThe arbiter function to be called
[in]user_dataPointer to user data to supply in the callback

◆ bcm_ptp_stack_create()

int bcm_ptp_stack_create ( int  unit,
bcm_ptp_stack_info_t *  ptp_info 
)

Create a PTP stack instance.

Create a PTP stack instance. As per PTP system design, TS0 and TS1 hardware timestamper can be running in either independently or in combined mode depending upon 1588 profile configuration. By default, TS0/TS1 timestamper will be in independent mode. In order to use telecom phase profile (G.8275.1/G.8273.2 ) , create the PTP stack with BCM_PTP_STACK_TIMESTAMPER_COMBINED_MODE.

Parameters
[in]unitUnit number.
[in,out]ptp_info(IN/OUT) Pointer to an PTP Stack Info structure
